x4freetext: 100 MeV proton beam on lithium target.
Beam monitoring by Faraday cup and TFBC.
Collimated neutron beam. About 50% of neutrons are in
96 MeV peak, the rest in low energy tail.
Neutron energy was derived from the angle of backward
elastic neutron-proton scattering and from energy of
Energy of incoming neutron was measured by TOF.
TFBC and Faraday cup - for beam monitoring.
To measure high-energy part of neutron spectrum
CLODIA (Chamber for LOcalization with DrIft and
Amplification) consists of seven (n,p) converters and
In addition, one SCANDAL arm was used to measure
CLODIA-SCANDAL efficiency was calculated by GEANT
simulation; depends of the emitted neutron energy
For low-energy part of neutron spectrum,
LPC Caen lab. DECOI- neutron-to-proton converter made
of plastic scintillator brick NE102, 5x9x15 cm**3.
DEMON - neutron detector made of cylindrical liquid
scintillator NE213 of 16 cm diameter, 20cm thickness.
In front of DEMON cell,5mm thick plastic scintillator
was added for charge particle rejection.
Specific simulation tool was developed to calculate
efficiency of DECOI-DEMON. Efficiency is typically one
order of magnitude smaller than that of CLODIA-SCANDAL.
For overlap energy region, from 40 to 50 MeV, the two
sets of measurement differ less than 10%.
